On Dec 31 2020, the number of covid cases were 1730 . Just a month later on Jan 31, the number of cases were 2948, an increase of more than 50%. this happened when new year celebrations were happening, and although there were strict social distancing rules (example: in order to attend the Burj Khalifa Fireworks, everyone was required to register on their app and use the generated QR code to enter the area) the numbers still went up. These numbers happened after 3m covid vaccines were administered in the UAE. With expo starting in less than 15 days, and the estimate being 25 million visitors over the next 6 months(that is around 4 million visitors a month and average of 138,000 per day) it is a far larger scale than new year's. Whether the UAE is ready for it or not is a different conversation, as they are fully ready to treat patients who have COVID 19 and have enough medical equipment and staff, so this probability doesn't question that.

Although the average of the COVID-19 cases has been in decline since late June 2021, there are multiple factors that could affect this desired curve. (1) One of the most evident factors could be the opening of Expo 2020 on October 1st, 2021, which is expecting a couple of million visitors from around the world, easing travel and commute restrictions (25 million visitors was the predicted number pre-COVID). [Internal thought: we may be looking at a 15 million average during COVID] Reference: https://www.bbc.com/news/business-56682427

I have started with a base prediction of 50% likelihood that 7-day average stays within the range of 501-1,499 cases because while the case count is currently at 803 as of Sep 12th and has been dropping at an average rate of 13 cases daily since the case peak on January 30th 2021, the country has still experienced several short spikes in the otherwise declining case count. Additionally, uncertainty about the level of breakthrough infections among the vaccinated and limited information on how many Emiratis and residents remain to be vaccinated (despite the government procuring at least enough vaccine of different types for all persons) make the ability of continued vaccination to further reduce the case count unclear. Lastly, several headwinds exist in the next 6 weeks that may challenge the current pace of decline including the recent end to travel restrictions for residents from India and other countries, the hosting of the world exception in Dubai in October, and the public holiday of Mawlid celebrated in mid-October. However, I rate an increase in the 7-day average to 1,500 or higher as a relatively low 20% because despite these headwinds, the state possess the means to reverse negative trends through a return to more stringent lockdown and travel restriction measures.
Due to screening & vaccination of population And safety measures taken in prep for EXPO

It's going down because the number of new cases yesterday was 620. In addition, cured cases have exceeded new cases. Also, more and more people are getting vaccinated against COVID-19, and this shows that about 79% of people have been vaccinated. So I think there will be a gradual decline in cases
As vaccines become more widely available, more than 70% of people get inject. Also, the cure rate is higher than the infection rate.

With 80% fully vaccinated, mask mandates in place and strict monitoring generally, I think the chance of a significant Delta wave is now quite low. I’d expect a slow decline to around 600 but I’ve learned that the numbers can shift dramatically once any natural immunity and vaccinations combine, so I’m prepared for it to slide lower. It’s a slight unknown how the recent opening of borders and upcoming Dubai Expo will affect cases, as testing will likely increase over this period, but given the above, any rise should be less extreme than before and is likely to be contained/policed, making a few plateaus between 600-1200 a realistic second option.

New cases yesterday were only 620. Total active cases fell below 7,000, as recoveries continue to exceed new cases. It's working almost like compound interest at this point, with cases falling, and it seems like it's at least a 9-in-10 chance of getting below 500 for a 7-day average sometime soon. The 90% threshold of total population getting one dose has now been passed, while 79% are fully vaccinated. The UAE is aggressively rolling out 3rd doses, including giving the powerful Pfizer vaccines to top up those who previously got Sinovac. I'm extremely hazy on the formula for herd immunity and I suspect there really isn't one for C19. You can't really plug in 1–1/R0 when immunity is less than full for those previously infected or fully vaccinated and different studies give you different numbers. However, just about every expert says the herd immunity threshold from vaccination is 90%. Even the naysayers will say something like: "Herd immunity is impossible. It would take 90% of the total population being vaccinated!"
Trending toward the 500 line.

So, we have 89% of the population of 10 million with at least one dose of COVID-19 vaccine and 78% fully vaccinated.[1] Let's figure breakthrough infections are something like 1 in 5,000-10,000 will have breakthrough infections in the fully vaccinated. So, something like 2,000-4,000 people are going to test positive even among the vaccinated.

My guess is that floor is very likely below 1500 (also given that the Govt has control of the news cycle), but it's not certain if the count < 500 in 2 months or so ( ~ 50% reduction)

UAE currently 87%/76% 1st dose/Fully vaccinated (according to Our World in Data which seems to conflict with the Business Insider article at the heading of the question). To form a first guess, Vermont has 76%/68% which is lower than UAE. But, if the UAE had the same current daily rate (.00023 X Population) as Vermont, it would be at 2300 cases daily. Right now the UAE is somewhat trending down from 1,000 and leveling out. Starting with the idea that these daily #'s tend to not stay in the same place and large moves up/down are the norm my first guess for this question might be 45/45/10 wrt >1500/<500/'neither'. Add 20% to '500 or lower' for higher vaccination rate and case trending downward. +5% to 'neither' for the trend rate flattening in the last week or two. 20/65/15 for an initial guess.
